╔═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║  MISSION: Station Network Identity                                            ║
║  DIFFICULTY: Beginner                                                         ║
║  STATUS: In Progress                                                          ║
╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

NEXUS: "Engineer, the station's network topology database was corrupted during
       the cascade failure. I need you to manually discover your workstation's
       network identity. Every device on Helios has a unique address - find
       yours, and we can begin rebuilding our network map."

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

OBJECTIVE
═════════
Before we can diagnose network issues, we must understand our own position in
the network. Every container on Helios Station has:

  - An IP Address: A unique identifier (e.g., 172.20.0.10)
  - A Subnet: The range of addresses in our network segment
  - A Default Gateway: The route to other networks
  - A DNS Server: How we translate names to addresses

Your task is to discover all of these for your workstation.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

TASKS
═════

[ ] Task 1: View Your IP Address
    Command: ip addr
    Look for the eth0 interface and note the IP address and subnet mask (/24)

[ ] Task 2: View Your Default Gateway
    Command: ip route
    Find the "default via X.X.X.X" line - this is your gateway

[ ] Task 3: Check DNS Configuration
    Command: cat /etc/resolv.conf
    Identify the nameserver IP address

[ ] Task 4: Resolve Another Container's Address
    Command: dig +short server
    Use DNS to find what IP the "server" container has

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

KEY CONCEPTS
════════════
  ip addr      - Shows all network interfaces and their addresses
  ip route     - Shows routing table (how to reach other networks)
  /etc/resolv.conf - System DNS configuration file
  dig          - DNS lookup utility

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

VERIFICATION
════════════
Create a file called 'network_info.txt' with three lines:
  Line 1: Your container's IP address (e.g., 172.20.0.10)
  Line 2: Your default gateway (e.g., 172.20.0.1)
  Line 3: Your DNS server address

Run: ./verify

Success: You can identify your workstation's IP, subnet, gateway, and DNS server.
The network map will begin to take shape.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

NEXT MISSION: cd ../connectivity && cat .mission
